The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Monday, March 01, 2004  Nation at a Glance				 																Court sex abuse poser to Nalco				 																																																	Mumbai (PTI): Bombay High Court has directed the National Aluminium Corporation (Nalco) to explain by March 3 whether it is following the Supreme Court guidelines with regard to sexual harassment at a workplace.				 																																																										The high court observation comes in the wake of molestation charges levelled by a woman employed at Nalco against its chairman-cum-managing director C. Venkataramana. 				 																																																										The direction was given on a petition filed by the woman who had sought protection and urged for a direction to the authorities to institute a departmental inquiry against the officers concerned.				 																																																										The woman urged that the inquiry should be launched against Venkataramana and regional manager Virendra Singh for their alleged misconduct with her at a city hotel on February 7.				 																																																										She feared that the company might transfer or victimise her for lodging a police complaint against the officials who had allegedly indulged in the molestation.				 																																																										Venkataramana was arrested on February 25 and released on bail. He had filed for an anticipatory bail in Delhi High Court but it was dismissed as withdrawn.				 																																																										Earlier, Singh was arrested and then granted bail on February 11. 				 																Indian in S. Africa raped amp; killed Durban (PTI): A woman of Indian origin was repeatedly raped and then murdered in the South African coastal city of Port Elizabeth, police said.				 																																																										Samantha Singh, 22, and her boyfriend were kidnapped by two men near the suburb of Cleary Park, while they were in a car.				 																																																										When the car ran out of fuel, she was raped by the hijackers in the car and her companion, Salvadore Bambi was tied up and stabbed in the face and head.				 																																																										The police said Bambi was able to free himself and run for help before being admitted to hospital in a serious condition.				 																																																										After an intensive search, the police arrested two suspects, who led them to where Singhs body lay.				 																																																										Singh had been stabbed in face several times and her throat had been slit.				 																																																										The police said the suspects would appear in court soon on charges of murder, attempted murder, rape, kidnapping and assault. 				 																Cops held for trader robbery				 																																																	Jaipur (PTI): Two police constables were arrested along with five others for robbing a businessman of Rs 4.5 lakh, police said on Sunday.				 																																																										The incident occurred on Saturday when some of the accused, posing as investors from Mumbai, approached Anshul Saini, offering a huge loan if he brought Rs 4.5 lakh as margin money. 				 																																																										Saini was asked to hand the cash to the driver of a car parked some distance away and take a draft for the loan amount. But when Saini was in the process of delivering the money, some persons dressed as cops snatched the cash and fled.				 																Rape probe				 																																																	Ahmedabad (PTI): A police team has been sent to Bhachau taluka in Kutch district to investigate the kidnap-cum-rape alleged by a 19-year-old girl there. The teenager said two persons had kidnapped her from the city on February 15 and raped her after taking her to Mumbai, police said. 				 																Scribe killed				 																																																	Shivpuri (PTI): A journalist was killed during a wedding ceremony when the groom and some others allegedly fired from their guns to celebrate the occasion in a village here. A bullet from groom Aruns pistol is said to have hit Dinesh Bhargav.				 																HIV directive				 																																																	Mumbai (PTI): Bombay High Court has directed the Union government to enumerate in an affidavit on March 3, the rules for considering extension of tenure for sailors in the navy who are HIV positive. The direction was given on a petition filed by a sailor who was refused extension as he is HIV positive.				 																Defence post				 																																																	New Delhi (PTI): Lt Gen. A.S. Bahia has been appointed the new director-general of military operations. Bahia takes over from Lt Gen. Balraj Singh Takhhar.				 																Dargah clean-up				 																																																	Ajmer (PTI): The decks have been cleared for the removal of encroachments on properties of the dargah of Khwaja Moinuddin Chishti here with its top official getting the status of estate officer. The nazim of the dargah committee was made estate officer by a legislative amendment.																		Efforts of the Tamil Nadu health department and NGOs to curb female infanticide seem to have paid off with only seven cases reported in 2003 against 65 in 2000. No case of female infanticide has been reported so far this year.
